	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> LOTR Q&A Rulings from 09/25/03<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.33)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=617'>Enrique "Max of Tat" Huerta</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=617&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> October 9, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Not for review.<br />
Originally posted on 09/25/03<br />
=============================<br />
<br />
Hello All!!<br />
<br />
   News about Return of the King is starting to hit the internet. The biggest impacts will be the new game mechanics (Initiative and Threats). So far initiative seems to be the more popular topic amoungst players because it brings up speculation of new cards to the x-list. Obviously The Palatir of Orthanc is mentioned often. (But to be honest, I think it would probably be mentioned even if Initiative had nothing to do with cards in hand.) (= I think it will be interesting to see if players start playing with cards like Tower of Barad-dur, Orc Inquisitor, and Hand of Sauron to help push the Free Peoples&#39; player into losing Initiative unexpectedly. And then of course there&#39;s the reaction of playing Erland and Frodo, Courteous Halfling to counter-act those strategies. It will be good to give the playing environment a little shake up, although I&#39;m going to miss playing with Reluctant Adventure if Initiative becomes too popular.<br />
<br />
   Essen and the World Cup is coming up soon also. DGMA just announced 2 sanctuary teams that will qualify from Day 1 into the Team versus Team matches. Everyone has a chance to qualify and play for the money! Well... almost everyone. (= Most of the major tournaments this year have been in the United States. It will be interesting to see what the meta is like in Europe, and what decks players from all over the world play.<br />
<br />
   Please remember that all previous rulings can be found in the Decktech Articles database. You can probably do a search, or just go to my DeckTech page for the links. Please don&#39;t feel you have to rated those &quot;articles&quot;. Although I do appreciate it, they aren&#39;t there to increase my tech points, they&#39;re there for you guys. (= Also, if you remember to leave your DeckTech name when you submit your questions, I&#39;ll try to send you the answer BEFORE I update the webpage every other Thursday. I&#39;m sure you&#39;d rather get your answer sooner that you do now. (=<br />
<br />
- Enrique<br />
<br />
<br />
<h3>Questions about Card Rulings:</h3><br />
<br />
<b>Let&#39;s say that my opponent has six companions in play. I was able to play exactly six minions, two of which is the Southron Commander. We directly go to the assignment phase, I assign the first Commander to Frodo which my opponent accepts (since Frodo has a sword)... can I assign the 2nd Commander to Frodo again even though he&#39;s currently assigned the 1st Commander? [Guimo]</b><br />
<br />
<i>Many assignment actions assign a minion to a companion. All of these assignments are &quot;one-on-one&quot; - you cannot assign one character to another unless both of them are unassigned. [Comprehensive Rulebook, pg 27, &quot;Perform Assignment Actions&quot;]</i><br />
<br />
So the first Southron Commender can be assigned to Frodo, but the second one could not because at the time to use his game text, Frodo is no longer unassigned.<br />
<br />
<b>Let&#39;s say there&#39;s a Cave Troll on the table with a Goblin Runner. The Cave Troll has his chain, which allows him to wound an archer companion if he takes a wound during the archery phase. The Free Peoples player has five archery and decides not to skip the archery phase. The Runner dies, and the Cave Troll takes wounds one at a time, wounding companions as this happens. My question is, can he do this for EACH wound he takes (ie four), or is he dead immediately after the fourth one, and therefore the Chain leaves play before he can activate its text? [Jason]</b><br />
<br />
Each archery wound the Cave Troll recieves will bearing the Cave Troll&#39;s Chain triggers an optional action to would an archer companion. However, when the Cave Troll received the fourth and final wound, the automatic action (which occur BEFORE optional actions) is to discard the Cave Troll and all cards on it. As such when the Cave Troll is killed you must discard the Chain before you have a change to use it a fourth time. Currently the most wounds you can dish out is 3.<br />
<br />
<b>frodo TT says that when you play a Ringbound ranger you may remove a burden, so can you remove 2 burdens at the beginning when you first play your starting fellowship? im wondering because you can remove one with pippin HOSI. thanks [Anders]</b><br />
<br />
<i>Game Text: Ring-bearer (resistance 10).Fellowship: Play a Ring-bound companion to remove a burden.</i><br />
<br />
Two things I want to point out. First, it&#39;s &quot;Ring-bound companion&quot; not &quot;Ring-bound ranger&quot;. This means you can also use this game text with Sam and Smeagol. Second (and most importantly) I want to point out that this is a <b>Fellowship:</b> action. That means you can only use it during the fellowship phase. Playing your starting fellowship does not occur during your fellowship phase, therefore you would not remove a burden.<br />
<br />
Pippin, Hobbit of Some Intelligence is different because his game text is not a fellowship action. His game text allows you to heal a companion or remove a burden every time he&#39;s played. Whether it&#39;s in the starting fellowship, the fellowship phase, or even the regroup phase.<br />
<br />
<b>I am playing Gondor Fortifications and Warg-Riders in my deck together, In a few solitaire hands, I ran into a conundrum. If I spot 3 Knights to transfer my fortification to a mounted warg rider, and that warg rider exerts to cancel that skirmish action, where does the fortification card go? Thanks.. [Robert]</b><br />
<br />
Using the Warg game text to prevent the Fortification from transferring would mean that the Fortification would remain in the support area. All costs (such as exerting companions would still be paid) but the Fortification would not transfer to the Warg-rider. Now if you &quot;Spot 3 knights&quot;, nothing prevents you from spotting them again, to again try to transfer the Fortification again. (You could also exert again if you wished.) Again they may exert the Warg-rider to prevent it, but at some point they will become exhausted and the Fortification will transfer anyways.<br />
<br />
<b>Hello Enrique, I have one question which is probbly answered but I must ask it again since in here there is great dispute over it. Lets say I have Saruman SOTE(4 vitality) on the table and LURTZ(so LURTZ is not firce) and opponent has Greenleaf with one exertion. HEre goes the situation 1. I use Saruman to assign LURTZ to Greenleaf 2. Opponent exert it to prevent 3. Can I use again Saruman to assign LURTZ to him in same assigment phase? Regards, N [Niki]</b><br />
<br />
You may preform any special ability with <b><i>phase action</i>:</b> as many times as you wish, as long you still meet the requirements and pay the costs. So if you&#39;re still able to meet the requirements (unassigned characters) and you can pay the costs (exert Saruman again) you may use Saruman&#39;s special ability more than once to assign a minion to skirmish Legolas. Please note that you may not assign more than one minion to a character because after the first one is assigned, you no longer meed the requirement of having unassigned characters.<br />
<br />
<h3>Questions about Game/Tournament Rulings:</h3><br />
<br />
<b>i was wondering if there is any rule about putting minions into your discard pile before your opponent decides whether to move again or not. this could affect whether you are going to move again, because either they would have discarded all of their minions and wouldn&#39;t have any out, or they wouldn&#39;t tell you what they had out and you wouldn&#39;t know whether to move based on their minions. what is the ruling, if any, regarding this situation? [Edwin]</b><br />
<br />
The proper procedure for the regroup phase is:<br />
 - Perform regroup actions<br />
 - Reconcile Shadow players&#39; hands<br />
 - Either the Free Peoples player move to the next site (return to Shadow phase) or the Free Peoples player reconciles their hand and the Shadow players discard all minions in play<br />
<br />
So as you can see, discarding the minions is something the Shadow players do AFTER the Free Peoples player has decided to move or not. Discarding the minions early is procedurally wrong and not something you should get in the habit of doing. Discarding minions is the last action of a turn, always.<br />
<br />
<b>A simple one: Can I look trough my opponents discard pile? Thanks for the answer. [Bert Claessen]</b> <br />
<br />
No. You may not look through your opponent&#39;s discard pile. The only card you&#39;re allowed to see is the top card. Note that anytime your opponent places a card in the discard pile you&#39;re allowed to see which card it is. So if you have a good memory you should be fine.<br />
<br />
- Enrique<br />
<br />
